Pool Allocators: Fast, Fixed-Size Allocation for Performance-Critical Code

The stack allocator we covered in Part 1 is ideal for nested, short-lived allocations. 
But what if you need to allocate many objects of the same size that live independently? 
A pool allocator is the answer.

The Core Idea
A pool allocator pre-allocates a large block of memory and divides it into fixed-size chunks. 
When you request memory, it hands out the next free chunk in constant time. When you free, it simply 
marks the chunk as available. No system calls, no fragmentation for same-sized objects.

class PoolAllocator {
public:
    PoolAllocator(std::size_t objectSize, std::size_t capacity)
        : mObjectSize(objectSize),
          mCapacity(capacity),
          mBuffer(std::make_unique<std::byte[]>(objectSize * capacity)),
          mFreeList(nullptr) {
        // Initialize free list with all chunks
        for (std::size_t i = 0; i < mCapacity; ++i) {
            auto* chunk = mBuffer.get() + (i * mObjectSize);
            *reinterpret_cast<void**>(chunk) = mFreeList;
            mFreeList = chunk;
        }
    }

    void* allocate() {
        if (mFreeList == nullptr)
            return nullptr;
        void* result = mFreeList;
        mFreeList = *reinterpret_cast<void**>(mFreeList);
        return result;
    }

    void deallocate(void* ptr) {
        *reinterpret_cast<void**>(ptr) = mFreeList;
        mFreeList = static_cast<std::byte*>(ptr);
    }

    void reset() {
        mFreeList = nullptr;
        for (std::size_t i = 0; i < mCapacity; ++i) {
            auto* chunk = mBuffer.get() + (i * mObjectSize);
            *reinterpret_cast<void**>(chunk) = mFreeList;
            mFreeList = chunk;
        }
    }

private:
    std::size_t mObjectSize;
    std::size_t mCapacity;
    std::unique_ptr<std::byte[]> mBuffer;
    std::byte* mFreeList;
};

How It Works
The pool maintains a singly-linked free list through the memory chunks themselves. Each free chunk stores a pointer to the next free chunk. Allocation pops from the list, deallocation pushes back. This gives O(1) allocation and deallocation.

The free list uses the allocated memory itself to store the next pointer when free. This is safe because the memory is unused when free, and we know the size is sufficient (the object size must be at least pointer-sized).

Usage Pattern
PoolAllocator particlePool(sizeof(Particle), 10000);

// Allocate particles
Particle* p1 = static_cast<Particle*>(particlePool.allocate());
Particle* p2 = static_cast<Particle*>(particlePool.allocate());
// ...

// Deallocate when done
particlePool.deallocate(p1);
particlePool.deallocate(p2);

// Or reset all at once
particlePool.reset();

When to Use a Pool Allocator

Game entities, particles, bullets — objects with identical size and independent lifetimes
Object pools for game development: enemies, projectiles, particles
Network packet buffers
Thread pools (allocating thread stack memory)
Database connection pools

Benefits

Constant time allocation and deallocation
No fragmentation for same-sized objects
No system call overhead after initialization
Memory reuse is automatic and instantaneous
Predictable performance

Tradeoffs

Fixed object size — cannot allocate different sizes
Fixed capacity — cannot grow beyond initial allocation
Memory is not returned to the system until pool is destroyed
Wasted memory if object size doesn't align well with typical allocations

Advanced: Polymorphic Pool
For multiple object types, you can create a polymorphic pool that uses placement new:

template <typename T>
class TypedPoolAllocator {
public:
    TypedPoolAllocator(std::size_t capacity)
        : mPool(sizeof(T), capacity) {}

    template <typename... Args>
    T* allocate(Args&&... args) {
        void* memory = mPool.allocate();
        return new (memory) T(std::forward<Args>(args)...);
    }

    void deallocate(T* ptr) {
        ptr->~T();
        mPool.deallocate(ptr);
    }

private:
    PoolAllocator mPool;
};

TypedPoolAllocator<Particle> particlePool(10000);
Particle* p = particlePool.allocate(position, velocity, lifetime);
particlePool.deallocate(p);

Comparison with Stack Allocator

Stack: LIFO order, nested lifetimes, variable sizes, bulk deallocation
Pool: Any order, independent lifetimes, fixed size, individual deallocation

Both eliminate system call overhead. Both provide predictable performance. Choose based on your allocation pattern.

Takeaways
A pool allocator trades flexibility for speed. When you know your object sizes and have a good estimate of maximum count,
it can eliminate allocation overhead entirely. It's the workhorse of game engines, real-time systems, and any code where object
churn is high but sizes are uniform.